<h2><span id="Caro-Kann_Defence">Caro-Kann Defence</span></h2>
<p>In choosing the Caro-Kann, Black gives up the centre in exchange for easier development. In contrast to the French, the queen's bishop is not blocked, but the c6-square is no longer available for the knight. Black often aims to let White's pawns overextend, or develop a poor structure, and take advantage in the endgame.
</p><p>White's natural move is now 2. d4 as nothing prevents them from building a strong center. Bobby Fischer sometimes played 2. Nf3 followed by 3. Nc3.
</p>
